## Root Cause & Recommendations

| Finding | Recommendation |
|---------|---------------|
| Ivanti VPN unpatched (CVE-2023-46805) | Implement mandatory patch SLA: Critical CVEs patched within 24 hours |
| LSASS not protected | Enable Credential Guard; restrict Task Manager dump via ASR rule |
| No MFA on VPN | Enforce phishing-resistant MFA (FIDO2) on all remote access |
| Rclone not blocked | Implement application allowlisting (Windows Defender Application Control) |
| VSS copies destroyed | Maintain immutable offline backups; test recovery quarterly |
| Lateral movement undetected | Tune CrowdStrike for PsExec + admin share detections; segment VLANs |

---

## Lessons Learned

-  Detection gap:  LSASS dump via Task Manager triggered a low-severity alert that was not actioned. A dedicated playbook for credential dumping detections — regardless of severity — would have shortened dwell time from 72 hours to under 4 hours.
-  Exfiltration detection:  280 GB leaving the network in 27 minutes should have triggered a DLP alert. Network egress baselining and anomaly alerting was absent.
-  Immutable backups were the deciding factor:  Recovery was possible within 48 hours due to an offline, air-gapped backup taken 7 days prior. Without it, estimated recovery time was 3–4 weeks.
